    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>New York</placeName>
                <add>נאכט לברתות</add>
                <date>Nov. 19. 1859</date>.</p>
            <p><addressee>Rev. Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>,
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My dear Sir—</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I have just received a letter from<lb/> my lawyer in
                    <placeName>Charleston</placeName> summoning me home, in the<lb/> most emphatic
                language, as my personal attendance at<lb/> the settlement of some worldy affair was
                indispensably<lb/> necessary. I have, therefore, being very busy with
                preparations<lb/> for my departure—only time to request you for the favor of<lb/>
                telling me, <hi rend="underline">by return of mail</hi>, <hi rend="underline"
                    >who</hi> sent you the correspond-<lb/>ence between myself and the committee
                presenting me the<lb/> Testimonial of some of my former flock. The
                cor-<lb/>respondence as published, but more so the accompanying<lb/> remarks make it
                appear, as tho' the presentation was<lb/> made <hi rend="underline">after</hi> I had
                refused the request to remain. Just<lb/> the reverse took place. The Ladies
                presented their gift on<lb/> the <date>18 of October</date>, the gentleman on the
                    <date>21</date>, in the morning,<lb/> and my replies to them bear the same dates
                respectively.<lb/> The petition—of which I <sic>sentt</sic> you a copy
                    <sic>inclosed</sic> with<lb/> this—was presented to me on <date>Friday</date>
                night, at the<lb/> Synagogue, after divine service, and answered by me on<lb/>
                <date>Sunday the 23d</date>, <hi rend="underline">a few hours before my departure
                    for</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline"><placeName>New-York</placeName></hi>. I don't wish that you
                should make any<lb/> public use of either this letter or the copy of the
                petition<lb/> accompanying this; both are communicated to you to give<lb/> you some
                intimation of the reason why I am anxious</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>to know who sent you the correspondence. Please, write<lb/> at once to the care of
                    <hi rend="underline">Prescott-House</hi>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With <persName>Mrs. M's</persName> &amp; my best regard,</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I remain, in the greatest<lb/> haste</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">Yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <persName role="author">M Mayer</persName>
            </p>
            <p>The Sabbath-Sunday movement of this city<lb/> is <hi rend="underline">exploded</hi>!
                The society has <hi rend="underline">dissolved</hi>! It<lb/> was a still-born
                child.</p>
        </body>
